<subSubSection lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="350" pageId="25" pageNumber="349" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[686,1201,724,1738]" box="[686,889,724,749]" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis box="[686,889,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">Taxonomic Notes</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[686,1201,724,1738]" lastBlockId="26.[130,645,163,292]" lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="350" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">
This is a small 
<emphasis box="[935,1030,758,783]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">
<taxonomicName box="[935,1027,758,783]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Murina</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The forearm lengths of the Thai specimens are 34.7 and 
<quantity box="[686,794,824,851]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.57" pageId="25" pageNumber="349" unit="mm" value="35.7">35.7 mm</quantity>
. The hairs on the dorsal pelage are dark brown with golden tips. The ventral pelage is paler, with dark roots and buff- brown tips (
<figureCitation box="[830,919,926,953]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[130,143,1679,1700]" captionTargetBox="[128,1202,410,1669]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[555,875,877,1362]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 2. A general view of part of Hala Forest and six bat species new to the fauna of Thailand: A — Hipposideros ridleyi, B — Myotis hermani, C — Murina suilla, D — Murina aenea, E — Kerivoula pellucida, F — Mops mops" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3944597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3944597/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">Fig. 2d</figureCitation>
). The ears have a small emargination on their posterior borders. Each wing is attached near to the base of the claw on the outer toe. The dorsal aspect of the tail membrane and the feet are cover- ed with golden hairs. The skull, with a condylo-canine length of 15.0– 
<quantity box="[1086,1196,1129,1156]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.54" pageId="25" pageNumber="349" unit="mm" value="15.4">15.4 mm</quantity>
, is larger than that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1840" box="[925,1028,1163,1189]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="suilla">
<emphasis box="[925,1028,1163,1189]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">M. suilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<tableCitation box="[1042,1131,1163,1190]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="24.[124,151,1717,1730]" captionTargetBox="[261,551,167,1727]" captionTargetId="graphics@24.[295,557,160,1733]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="TABLE 5. Eleven cranial and dental measurements (in mm) of 11 specimens of eight bat species recently collected in Thailand, including the greatest length of skull (GTL), condylo-basal length (CBL), condylo-canine length (CCL), zygomatic breadth (ZB), breadth of braincase (BB), postorbital constriction (PC), maxillary toothrow length (C–M 3), palatal breadth (M 3 – M 3), anterior palatal breadth (C 1 – C 1), mandibular toothrow length (C–M), mandibular length (M). For Murina suilla, 3 the range, mean and standard deviation are given" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">Table 5</tableCitation>
). The rostrum is more robust and the anterior part is slightly bulbous when viewed laterally. There is a well developed rostral sulcus and a sagittal crest is present. The upper toothrows are not conspicuously convergent. The second upper incisor (I 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1145,1155,1361,1380]" fontSize="8" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">3</superScript>
) is equal in height, has twice the crown area, and is situated alongside the bicuspid first (I 
<superScript attach="right" box="[706,716,1463,1482]" fontSize="8" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">2</superScript>
), which in consequence is scarcely visible when viewed laterally. The first upper canine (C 
<superScript attach="left" box="[803,813,1530,1549]" fontSize="8" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">1</superScript>
) is equal to, or larger than, the second upper premolar (P 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1005,1015,1564,1583]" fontSize="8" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">4</superScript>
) when viewed laterally and has an equal crown area. The mesostyle of the first (M 
<superScript attach="left" box="[977,987,1632,1651]" fontSize="8" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">1</superScript>
) and second (M 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1179,1189,1632,1651]" fontSize="8" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">2</superScript>
) upper molars is greatly reduced. In the low- er dentition, the first premolar (P 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1078,1088,1719,1738]" fontSize="8" pageId="25" pageNumber="349">2</subScript>
) is about 60% of the crown area of the second (P 
<subScript attach="left" box="[618,628,178,197]" fontSize="8" pageId="26" pageNumber="350">4</subScript>
). The talonids of the first (M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[476,486,212,231]" fontSize="8" pageId="26" pageNumber="350">1</subScript>
) and second (M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[166,176,247,266]" fontSize="8" pageId="26" pageNumber="350">2</subScript>
) lower molars are smaller than the trigonid.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="350" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="26.[130,646,335,1082]" box="[130,536,335,361]" pageId="26" pageNumber="350">
<emphasis box="[130,536,335,361]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="350">Distribution and Ecological Notes</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[130,646,335,1082]" pageId="26" pageNumber="350">
Currently, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hill" authorityYear="1964" box="[301,419,370,395]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Murina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="350" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aenea">
<emphasis box="[301,419,370,395]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="350">M. aenea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recorded from peninsular 
<collectingCountry box="[265,373,404,430]" name="Malaysia" pageId="26" pageNumber="350">Malaysia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[439,511,404,430]" country="Malaysia" name="Sabah" pageId="26" pageNumber="350">Sabah</collectingRegion>
in Borneo (
<bibRefCitation author="MEDWAY, LORD" bookContentInfo="106 pp." box="[138,324,438,464]" journalOrPublisher="Oxford University Press, Kuala Lumpur" pageId="26" pageNumber="350" refId="ref24283" refString="MEDWAY, LORD. 1969. The wild mammals of Malaya and offshore islands including Singapore. Oxford University Press, Kuala Lumpur, 106 pp." title="The wild mammals of Malaya and offshore islands including Singapore" type="book" year="1969">Medway, 1969</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="HILL, J. E. &amp; C. M. FRANCIS" box="[344,632,438,464]" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Brit- ish Museum Natural History (Zoology)" pageId="26" pageNumber="350" pagination="305 - 329" part="47" refId="ref21854" refString="HILL, J. E., and C. M. FRANCIS. 1984. New bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) and new records of bats from Borneo and Malaya. Bulletin of the Brit- ish Museum Natural History (Zoology), 47: 305 - 329." title="New bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) and new records of bats from Borneo and Malaya" type="journal article" year="1984">Hill and Francis, 1984</bibRefCitation>
). This is the first record from 
<collectingCountry box="[465,573,472,498]" name="Thailand" pageId="26" pageNumber="350">Thailand</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[130,646,335,1082]" pageId="26" pageNumber="350">
In Hala Forest, it was captured in a harp trap set over a small stream (
<quantity box="[466,512,541,568]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="26" pageNumber="350" unit="m" value="4.0">4 m</quantity>
wide). The area is relatively flat, with an elevation of less than 
<quantity box="[245,322,610,636]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="26" pageNumber="350" unit="m" value="200.0">200 m</quantity>
a.s.l. The vegetation com- prises pristine lowland evergreen forest with a lower storey of dense shrub and sapling cover. It is ca. 
<quantity box="[390,463,713,740]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="26" pageNumber="350" unit="m" value="500.0">500 m</quantity>
from a river. In Ton Nga-chang, it was caught in a harp trap set at ground level along a trail leading to a waterfall. The trail is on a foothill, which as has an elevation of about 
<quantity box="[497,578,850,877]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="26" pageNumber="350" unit="m" value="200.0">200 m</quantity>
a.s.l. and is close to a stream. The vegetation is undisturbed lowland evergreen forest. The canopy (
<quantity box="[290,354,953,980]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="26" pageNumber="350" unit="m" value="30.0">30 m</quantity>
in height) is dominated by large dipterocarps while the ground lay- er is moderately covered with shrubs and herbs.
</paragraph>
